column3: feature_definition
A dendritic cell that captures antigens in a lung and migrates to a lymph node or to the spleen to activate T cells.
An ON bipolar cell type with dendrites selectively contacting S-cones.

An OFF calbindin-positive bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and stratifies narrowly close to the middle of the inner plexiform layer. Its axon terminal is characterized by regularly branching and varicose processes resembling beads on a string. Most of DB3a contacts with cones are triad-associated.
A spermatid in an early stage of maturation that has a round morphology and is transcriptionally active.

column2: airway submucosal gland duct basal cell
column3: A basal cell that is part of a duct of an airway submucosal gland.
column8: basal cell of duct in airway submucosal gland

column3: A fibroblast that is part of the fibrous layer of the perichondrium. This cell is responsible for collagen fiber production.
column8: fibroblast of fibrous layer of perichondrium

column3: An ON bipolar cell with a small dendritic tree that forms most of the central (invaginating) elements opposite the synaptic ribbon at the cone triad.
column8: ON bipolar cell with small dendritic tree

column3: A medium spiny neuron that exhibits transcriptional divergence from direct and indirect spiny projection neurons, for example, enrichment in Casz1, Otof, Cacng5 and Pcdh8 noted in mice. Whilst in general medium spiny neurons have been found to be differentially distributed across the basal ganglia, the eccentric medium spiny neuron cell type has been found to be more evenly distributed throughout cerebral nuclei.
A medium spiny neuron that expresses both DRD1 and DRD2 and is part of an extra-striosomal part of dorsal striatum.
column8: medium spiny neuron with dual dopamine receptor expression

column3: An alveolar macrophage that expresses metallothionein.
An ON diffuse bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and large axon terminals, which show little or no overlap. This cell predominantly connects to narrow thorny ganglion cells.
A macrophage that is part of the lung connective tissue (pulmonary interstitium). This cell performs tissue remodeling and contributes to barrier immunity through antigen presentation.
An alveolar macrophage that expresses CCL3.

A glial precursor cell that generates oligodendrocytes and type-1 and type-2 astrocytes. It has been shown in some mammals that this cell type may express A2B5, nestin, FGFR-1, FGFR-2, FGFR-3, PLP, and DM-20 antigens. Unlike oligodendrocyte precursor cell, it does not initially express PDGFR-alpha and can differentiate into both type-1 and type-2 astrocytes.

column2: lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell
column3: An alpha-beta CD8 T cell that resides in the lung.

column2: mucus secreting cell of bronchus submucosal gland
column3: A mucus secreting cell of a submucosal gland of the bronchus.
column8: mucus secreting cell of bronchus submucosal gland

column3: A neuron that releases catecholamine as a neurotransmitter.
An ON diffuse bipolar cell that predominantly connects to ON parasol cells and lateral amacrine cells.
A ciliated cell of the endometrial glandular epithelium.
column8: ciliated cell of endometrial glandular epithelium

column3: An epithelial cell part of respiratory tract epithelium that is a precursor of a multi-ciliated cell. This cell actively amplifies centrioles, a required step for multiciliogenesis.
column8: precursor cell of respiratory tract epithelium

column3: A megakaryocyte that is resident in the lung connective tissue.
A taste receptor cell that is part of a taste bud of a tongue.
A DRD2-expressing medium spiny neuron that is part of a matrix compartment of dorsal striatum.
An OFF bipolar cell that is fovea-specific and expresses FEZF1, NXPH1 and NXPH2.

A myofibroblast that is part of an alveoli during alveolarization. The contractile force of this cell elongates the secondary crest, while producing a framework of elastin and tenascin. During the maturation of the septa, secondary crest myofibroblasts, together with matrix fibroblasts, secrete metalloproteinases and other ECM‚Äêremodeling proteins to thin the septal tip ECM. The secondary crest myofibroblast continues producing elastin, eventually undergoing apoptosis during adulthood.
An OFF diffuse bipolar cell that predominantly connects to ON parasol cells and lateral amacrine cells. This cell contains a large number of synaptic ribbons and a small axon arbor area.

A urothelial cell that is terminally differentiated and part of the urothelial apical surface that forms the high-resistance barrier of urothelium. Umbrella cells have been described as the largest of urothelial cell types, highly polarized, and, in some species, multinucleated. In the relaxed state, these cells form a dome-shaped structure at the apical pole and can also cover multiple underlying intermediate cells, leading to the name umbrella cells. In contrast, these cells flatten when the bladder is filled.

column2: nucleus accumbens shell and olfactory tubercle D2 medium spiny neuron
column3: A DRD2-expressing medium spiny neuron that is part of a nucleus accumbens shell or olfactory tubercle.

A respiratory epithelial cell with topographic nuclear position in between the basal and luminal cell of the airway epithelium. This non-basal, intermediate cell has limited proliferative capacity, ultrastructural features of basal cells and no defined features of the typically differentiated cellular phenotypes.

Glial cell that provides support to the enteric nervous system. It is involved in enteric neurotransmission, in maintaining the integrity of the mucosal barrier of the gut and serves as a link between the nervous and immune systems of the gut. In enteric nerve strands, glial processes ensheath multiaxonal bundles which distinguishes enteric glia from all other peripheral glia. Ultrastructurally, the most conspicuous trait of an enteroglial cell is the presence of 10 nm filaments, which criss-cross the cell body, form axial bundles in the processes and appear to firmly anchor the cells to the ganglionic surfaces. Similar to astrocytes, their main constituent is glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP).

column2: lung resident memory CD8-positive, CD103-positive, alpha-beta T cell
column3: A lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell that is CD103-positive.
column8: lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell that is CD103-positive

column3: A ciliated cell of the respiratory system. Ciliated cells are present in airway epithelium.

column2: CD24-positive, CD-133-positive, vimentin-positive proximal tubular cell
column3: A CD24-positive, CD-133-positive, vimentin-positive cell found scattered throughout a renal proximal tubule and that may participate in tubular regeneration. Compared to other proximal tubular cell types, this cell contains less cytoplasm, fewer mitochondria and no brush border.

An OFF calbindin-negative bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and stratifies narrowly close to the middle of the inner plexiform layer. Its axon terminal is characterized by regularly branching and varicose processes resembling beads on a string. Most of DB3b contacts with cones are non-triad-associated.
A ciliated cell of the endometrial epithelium. The cilia of this cell type help move mucus from glandular tissue of the endometrium.
column8: ciliated cell of the endometrial epithelium

column3: An OFF bipolar cell with a small dendritic tree that provides most of the triad-associated basal (flat) contacts at cone pedicles.
column8: OFF bipolar cell with small dendritic tree

column3: A DRD1-expressing medium spiny neuron that is part of a matrix compartment of dorsal striatum.
column8: DRD1-expressing medium spiny neuron in matrix compartment of dorsal striatum

column2: lung resident memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell
column3: An alpha-beta CD4 T cell that resides in the lung.
column8: alpha-beta CD4 T cell in the lung

column3: A smooth muscle cell that is part of a bronchiole.

column2: mucus secreting cell of tracheobronchial tree submucosal gland
column3: A mucus secreting cell of a submucosal gland of the tracheobronchial tree.
column8: mucus secreting cell of airway submucosal gland in tracheobronchial tree

column3: A DRD2-expressing medium spiny neuron that is part of a striosome of dorsal striatum.
A DRD1-expressing, medium spiny neuron-like granule cell that is part of an Island of Calleja.
column8: DRD1-expressing medium spiny neuron-like granule cell

column3: A star-shaped glial cell that is part of some retina. This cell links neurons to blood vessels and may provide structural and physiological support to optic nerve head axons.

A urothelial cell that is part of the regenerative layer(s) of cells directly superficial to basal cells in urothelium. The layer of intermediate cells in the urothelium ranges from one to several layers thick depending on the species with intermediate cells attached to adjacent cell layers and one another via desmosomes.
A perichondrial fibroblast that is part of the lung.
An OFF diffuse bipolar cell that makes synaptic contact with both L/M and S-cone photoreceptors and only minimal contact with rod photoreceptors.
A horse-specific, highly invasive trophoblast cell that invades the endometrium where it forms endometrial cups.
Precursor of type II pneumocyte. These cells do not have lamellar bodies, which are a marker of type II pneumocyte maturity.
A spermatid in a late stage of maturation that has an elongated morphology and is transcriptionally inert when the acrosome is fully developed.
A dental pulp cell that possesses stem-cell-like qualities, including self-renewal capability and multi-lineage differentiation.
column8: dental pulp cell with stem-cell-like qualities
